Server Components render ONLY on the server — zero JS shipped to client.

• They can directly access databases, filesystems, and APIs
• No useState, no useEffect, no event handlers
• They reduce bundle size dramatically
• Children can be Client Components (but not vice-versa)

Why? Performance + DX:
• Less JS = faster load
• Co-locate data fetching with UI
• Automatic code splitting

```jsx
// This runs on the server only
async function UserList() {
  const users = await db.query('SELECT * FROM users');
  return <ul>{users.map(u => <li key={u.id}>{u.name}</li>)}</ul>;
}
```

They mark state updates as LOW PRIORITY so urgent updates (typing, clicking) stay fast.

useTransition:
• Returns [isPending, startTransition]
• isPending = true while transition is rendering

```jsx
const [isPending, startTransition] = useTransition();

function handleSearch(query) {
  setInputValue(query);           // urgent — updates input immediately
  startTransition(() => {
    setFilteredResults(filter(query)); // deferred — won't block input
  });
}
```

When to use:
• Filtering large lists while user types
• Tab switching with heavy re-renders
• Navigation transitions

Key: React can interrupt the low-priority render if a high-priority update arrives.

forwardRef passes a ref through a component to a child DOM node or component.

```jsx
const FancyInput = forwardRef((props, ref) => (
  <input ref={ref} className="fancy" {...props} />
));
// Parent: <FancyInput ref={inputRef} />
```

useImperativeHandle customizes WHAT the ref exposes (instead of the raw DOM node):
```jsx
const FancyInput = forwardRef((props, ref) => {
  const inputRef = useRef();
  useImperativeHandle(ref, () => ({
    focus: () => inputRef.current.focus(),
    clear: () => { inputRef.current.value = ''; }
  }));
  return <input ref={inputRef} {...props} />;
});
```

When to use:
• forwardRef — reusable UI components that wrap DOM elements
• useImperativeHandle — expose limited API (focus, scroll, play)
• Avoid for data flow — prefer props/state. Refs are escape hatches.

Note: React 19 passes ref as a regular prop — forwardRef may become optional.

Custom hooks extract and reuse stateful logic. Name must start with 'use'.

Best practices:
• Single responsibility — one hook, one concern
• Return stable references (memoize callbacks/objects)
• Accept configuration as params, not globals
• Return [value, actions] or { data, error, loading } — consistent shape

```jsx
function useLocalStorage(key, initial) {
  const [value, setValue] = useState(() => {
    const stored = localStorage.getItem(key);
    return stored ? JSON.parse(stored) : initial;
  });
  useEffect(() => {
    localStorage.setItem(key, JSON.stringify(value));
  }, [key, value]);
  return [value, setValue];
}
```

Patterns:
• useToggle, useDebounce, useMediaQuery — utility hooks
• useFetch, useMutation — data hooks
• useForm, useAuth — domain hooks

Avoid: hooks that do too many things or have 10+ params.

Error boundaries catch JS errors in the component tree and render a fallback UI.

• Class component only (no hook equivalent yet)
• Uses static getDerivedStateFromError() and componentDidCatch()

```jsx
class ErrorBoundary extends React.Component {
  state = { hasError: false };
  static getDerivedStateFromError(error) {
    return { hasError: true };
  }
  componentDidCatch(error, info) {
    logToService(error, info.componentStack);
  }
  render() {
    if (this.state.hasError) return <FallbackUI />;
    return this.props.children;
  }
}
```

What they DON'T catch:
• Event handlers (use try/catch)
• Async code (promises, setTimeout)
• SSR errors
• Errors in the boundary itself

Tips:
• Use react-error-boundary library for hooks-friendly API
• Place boundaries at route level + around risky widgets
• Include a 'retry' button in fallback UI

React 19 major additions:

• use() hook — read promises and context in render:
```jsx
function UserName({ userPromise }) {
  const user = use(userPromise); // suspends until resolved
  return <span>{user.name}</span>;
}
```

• Actions — async functions for transitions:
```jsx
const [error, submitAction, isPending] = useActionState(
  async (prevState, formData) => {
    const result = await saveUser(formData);
    if (result.error) return result.error;
  }, null
);
```

• Form actions — <form action={fn}> for progressive enhancement
• useFormStatus — get pending state inside form children
• useOptimistic — show optimistic UI before server confirms
• ref as prop — no more forwardRef needed
• Document metadata — <title>, <meta> in components
• Stylesheet precedence — built-in CSS loading coordination
